> *        *        *
>
> Jamadagni
>  (jamat+agni=constantly consuming fire) stands for divine awareness.
> Renuka (renu=particle) stands for matter. She was so pure that she could
>  hold water in a pot made of unbaked clay. When purified matter is
> infused with divine awareness, it gives rise to a perfected form of
> happiness or bliss.
>
> This happiness is liberating in nature and
> so Bhargava Rama is a brahmana and a rishi. This perfected form of
> happiness is also too powerful and tends to dominate over other forces
> within one. So Bhargava Rama also had kshatriya qualities &
> ancestry.
>
> When Renuka was enamored by a gandharva called
> Chitraratha (chitra=strange, ratha=desire), Jamadagni ordered Bhargava
> Rama to kill her. When the material that was instrumental in giving rise
>  to bliss is tainted with strange attachment, it needs to be cut off and
>  be recreated pure. Bhargava Rama made Renuka alive again by asking
> Jamadagni for a boon after obeying his word.
>
> Later, Jamadagni
> was killed by Kartavirya Arjuna, a great king, and that greatly
> disturbed Bharga Rama. Kartavirya means "coming from Kritavirya".
> Kritavirya means one who has engaged in bravery. Coming from the verb
> rij (be firm and steady), Arjuna stands for steadiness and firmness.
> "Kartavirya Arjuna" stands for firmness and confidence coming from
> having engaged in bravery. When that cuts off the constant fire of
> divine awareness (Jamadagni) in one, that greatly disturbs the poise of
> one's bliss (Bhargava Rama). One's bliss returns to normal only after
> destroying all instincts of domination, pride, control and power inside
> one (kshatriyas). Such instincts and bliss do not go together well. So
> Bhargava Rama disliked kshatriyas for ever.
>
> However, Lord Rama
> was one kshatriya who Bhargava Rama had to bow to. As discussed before,
> Lord Rama is Sun (soul). Supreme are the power and command of soul,
> which keeps on magnanimously supporting various aspects of
> individualized consciouness in their pursuits. It is immensely strong
> and powerful and no wonder Rama was a kshatriya. Despite the supremely
> heroic work done by soul in supporting its subjects, it is perfect in
> detachment and has no agendas of its own. Finally Bhargava Rama met a
> kshatriya who was not only strong and heroic, but also had Brahma Tejas.
>  He had to bow. Similarly, bliss may be averse to instincts of heroic
> strength and control as they tend to disturb bliss, but, when bliss
> meets soul, it sees a powerful hero with perfect abandon, who is the
> source of various kinds of bliss.
>
> *        *        *
>
> Similarly,
>  story of Lord Koorma demonstrates how persistence/patience in us
> operates in its perfected form, its nature, challenges it faces etc.
> Story of Lord Narasimha demonstrates how energy/drive in us operates in
> its perfected form, its nature, challenges it faces etc. And so on.
>
> Our
>  scriptures are not filled with meaningless stories. They are true
> stories of events in some other realms of being. They also
> metaphorically represent great inner truths that may occur within us.
> They can help us understand ourselves, how we can perfect various
> aspects of our personalities and how we can progress.
>
