>>I want to emphatically disagree with this notion that Dasavatars of a
>> "linear progression of spirituality..upto Krshna".
>>
>>*        *        *
>>
>>Each avatara represents an aspect of Supreme in a perfected form.
>>
>>Maharshi Parasara equated dasavataras with planets. For example, Rama,
>> Krishna and Narasimha are Sun, Moon and Mars, respectively.
>>
>>We also
>  know that Sun, Moon, Mars, Mercury, Jupiter, Venus, Saturn, Rahu and Ketu
> are personifications of soul, mind, energy/initiative/drive, learning
> spirit, wisdom/discrimination, spirit of enjoyment/being happy,
> patience/discipline, spirit of innovation/breaking barriers and detachment
> (respectively).
>>
>>Correspondingly, each avatara is an expression of that aspect of Supreme in
>> a perfected form. Each story is an example of how that aspect operates.
>>
>>Lord Rama's story is a perfected example of how soul operates. Lord
>> Krishna's story is a perfected example of how mind operates. Lord Vamana's
>> story is a perfected example of how wisdom/discrimination operates. Lord
>> Narasimha's story is a perfected example of how energy/drive/initiative
>> operates.
>>
>>*        *        *
>>
>>Now, let us remember one basic thing. Soul in us, mind in us, energy in
>> us,
>  learning spirit in us, wisdom in us, happiness in us, discipline/patience
> in us - all these are different manifestations of the same Self. However,
> when Self manifests as these different aspects, it has different qualities
> and plays different roles. There is no comparison between them.
>>
>>We MAY focus on one aspect of us first, perfect it and then perfect other
>> aspects through it. But, we need balance between all aspects in the end.
>> Similarly, these different aspects of Supreme Being are incomparable and
>> are in a balance working together in the Cosmos.
>>
>>*        *        *
>>
>>One who is fascinated by the qualities of soul may like the story that
>> demonstrates how soul operates; one who is fascinated by the qualities of
>> mind may like the story that demonstrates how mind operates, and one who
>> is fascinated by the qualities of wisdom may like the story that
>  demonstrates how wisdom operates. And so on. But this is just a matter of
> taste and subjective preference.
>>
>>*        *        *
>>
>>Let us focus on Rama and Krishna, i.e. soul and mind. Soul is seen as a
>> representative of god in us, because of some basic attributes of it. It is
>> the higher self and has no agendas, no likes or dislikes.
>>
>>Once mind fancies a separate existence with some agendas/desires, soul
>> supports the individualized consciousness stemming from that fancy and
>> sees it as its dharma. It lends strength and support to EVERY aspect of
>> this individualized consciousness (e.g. mind, energy, intellect, learning
>> ability, enjoyment, discipline etc). It supports them fully and yet has no
>> desires/agendas/likes/dislikes of its own! It impassionately witnesses and
>> records all of one's agendas and karmas so that Laws of Nature give proper
>> fruits later
>  on. It does all that despite full awareness that it is neither doing those
> karmas nor receiving the fruits. As mind and other aspects of the
> individualized consciousness entertain the notion that they are doing things
> and begetting the fruits, soul supports them fully in this play. It sees
> that as its dharma and does it impassionately.
>>
>>Now, does this sound exciting? Perhaps not to all. This functionality of an
>> impassionate witness supporting the play, may not seem interesting enough
>> to some.
>>
>>On the other hand, mind has likes, dislikes and agendas. It is constantly
>> pursuing those agendas, getting things and achieving things. Movement of
>> mind is what keeps the individualization going!!! Though soul is the
>> support for everything else in the individualized consciousness, soul is a
>> witness doing its dharma impassionately. It is mind that keeps the
>> individualization going and brings in agendas and passion and even
>> decides/affects
>  every entity's dharma. That way, mind is really the "boss" of the
> individualization. No wonder Krishna's life appeals more to one who may be
> excited by this description!
>>
>>*        *        *
>>
>>Lord Krishna is obviously awe-inspiring, but let me put Rama's life in
>> perspective.
>>
>>Rama's life demonstrates how soul operates. At a young age, he received
>> Brahma Jnana from Vasishtha and became realized. Yet, he did whatever was
>> his "dharma". He helped Vishwamitra. Soon after marriage, he was given
>> kingdom. At the last moment, his father banished him to forest at the
>> behest of his step-mother and his step-brother was given the throne. He
>> had no complaints. Though his father, step-mother and step-brother felt
>> guilty to various degrees, he himself supported and consoled all three and
>> followed his dharma impassionately. Though he knew leaving Sita in the
>> forest
>  with Lakshmana and going after the golden deer would cause problems, he did
> it impassionately when Sita insisted. When she was kidnapped by Ravana, he
> searched for her and fought the battle. He never faulted Sita for forcing
> him to leave her or faulted Lakshmana for leaving her later. He accepted
> every life situation with no complaints and did the best possible action
> then. Even as he killed Ravana, he did so without hatred or anger, but as
> his impassionate dharma. Even as Ravana was dying, he went to him and
> respectfully learned some subjects that were going to disappear with
> Ravana!
>>
>>Rama is a perfect example of a liberated man with no desires or agendas who
>> impassionately discharges one's dharma arising from the momentum of karmas
>> before liberation. THAT is basically what soul does!
>>
